## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 42 [Considerations] below from 1 to 7, where 1 is strongly disagree and 7 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 42 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 42 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Street scene in Uppsala has changed for the worse since the beggars have come.
2. Sweden can not take responsibility for all the poor people in the world.
3. Many beggars are victims.
4. Beggars should not bring their children to Sweden but leave them at home so they can attend school.
5. EU migrants coming to Uppsala due to rumors of more support and shelter for the homeless.
6. The beggars trying to cheat me out of money by playing sick and poor even though they are not.
7. If we begin to help those who come here to beg for it will soon be even more.
8. We need to focus on giving them help in their homeland.
9. Before we assist foreign beggars, we must take care of our own Swedish homeless.
10. The beggars have it good here in Sweden and would rather live here. 
11. Home countries Romania and Bulgaria have a responsibility to improve the situation of their minority population.
12. Beggars can get away with things that you and I would not get away with.
13. The migrant beggars are eating way the Swedish welfare state
14. They should look for jobs instead of begging.
15. Beggars have the same values as us and therefore we have an obligation to help them with school, work, housing and food.
16. Politicians in Uppsala take no responsibility for the beggars.
17. We should take in more refugees in Sweden.
18. I have no responsibility for helping the begging Roma in Sweden.
19. It is our establishment which invites them to beg and take part of our social safety net.
20. The EU is responsible to handle the situation involving EU citizens crossing borders to beg.
21. The EU is powerless against Romania's shameless treatment of the Roma minority.
22. It's good to give money to the beggars
23. We must improve the beggars conditions when they are in Sweden.
24. The emergence of "parallel societies" and "slums" in Uppsala, is not acceptable.
25. The municipality is responsible for helping the begging EU citizens in Sweden.
26. Allowing street begging in some EU countries, including Sweden, does not facilitate Romania's efforts to achieve social inclusion and enhancing employability
27. Begging EU Citizens really want to go back to their country and not live in Sweden.
28. It is not OK to break Swedish law just because the offenders are poor.
29. Our tax money should go to the Swedes not to foreign beggars.
30. Begging on the streets of Uppsala is organized with connections to the criminal mafia.
31. I feel guilty that I have it good when I see a beggar.
32. Why don't we just treat the beggars the same as we do refugees? They are in the same situation.
33. Begging is caused by poverty and discrimination of minority groups in certain EU countries.
34. We can not help so much that we are sending the wrong signals.
35. I feel helpless when I see a beggar.
36. Beggars are victims of poverty in their home countries.
37.  Romania is failing to take responsibility for the Roma population.
38. Tourism in Sweden is damaged when the image of a clean and safe country no longer proves correct.
39. We should try the beggars to find other ways to help themselves.
40. There are too many beggars on the streets of Uppsala.
41. There is no ultimate responsibility for begging EU citizens.
42. The Swedish state is responsible for helping the begging Roma in Sweden.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Forbid giving money to beggars
2. Provide accommodation for beggars (more)
3. Ban Illegal Settlements
4. Enforce existing laws without special consideration for beggars
5. Ban Begging within Sweden
6. Focus resources on addressing the the problem in source countries such as Romania
7. Deport any immigrants found begging on the streets who have stayed in Sweden longer than three months

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Prioritize addressing root causes in source countries while enforcing laws fairly and providing limited support locally.

## [Example output]:

2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. When it comes to the Bloomfield Track, it's not important to worry about what the future will hold
2. A long term perspective on the Bloomfield Track is essential.
3. In deciding on what to do with the Bloomfield Track I don't know whether it's more important to meet the needs of the community or the environment.
4. Using cars on the Bloomfield Track is bad for the rainforest.
5. No development should be permitted in World Heritage areas such as the Daintree.
6. The coral reefs along the foreshore below the Bloomfield Track are not badly affected by the road.
7. Whilst impacts on locals in the Bloomfield area are a concern, it is the broader community that should carry more weight when deciding what to do with the Bloomfield Track.
8. I would be worse off if more of the Daintree rainforest is protected.
9. If the Bloomfield Track is sealed (bitumenized) there will not be a rapid increase in environmentally damaging development in the Daintree area in the future It may even benefit the environment there.
10. The Bloomfield Track may not have been the best idea, but I guess there is probably little point in closing it now that it has been built.
11. I'm not sure if the future of the Bloomfield Track should be determined by locals, outsiders or both.
12. Everyone in Queensland is better off for having a road like the Bloomfield Track.
13. The road is just the 'thin edge of the wedge'. This may not happen for a long time, but it will happen.
14. Conservation in the Daintree area is worthwhile at whatever cost.
15. When it comes to the Bloomfield track, people living in Cairns are in no position to judge what the interests of the local residents of Bloomfield are.
16. Any decision about the Bloomfield Track will greatly affect people like me.
17. I have no idea what the people in the Bloomfield area think about the Bloomfield Track.
18. The Bloomfield Track issue is important for Queensland.
19. The future of the Bloomfield Track should be determined by everyone and not just by those who live in the Bloomfield area.
20. I don't know if improving the Bloomfield Track would lead to a rapid acceleration of development in the area to the detriment of the environment.
21. The fate of the Bloomfield Track is of no concern to me.
22. Erosion from the Bloomfield Track is permanently damaging the coral reefs that fringe the beaches below
23. The Wujal Wujal Community is better off now that the Bloomfield Track has been built.
24. Let's fix the problems in the Daintree just for now. The future will take care of itself.
25. I don't know what the people of Bloomfield think about the Bloomfield Track.
26. I don't like how development is creeping further and further North into the Daintree and beyond because of its effect on the environment.
27. I don't know how, but I think that there must be some way in which everybody benefits from protecting the rainforest near the Bloomfield Track.
28. If we don't take steps to protect the Daintree Rainforest future generations will miss out on the opportunity to experience the area as we do now.
29. If future generations could have their say about the Bloomfield track, they would be less concerned about the environmental impacts than many people make out.
30. The protection of plants and animals in the Daintree is OK so long as it doesn't affect me.
31. I don't really know who benefits most from the protection of Rainforest in the Daintree.
32. We don't need to worry too much about environmental damage in the Daintree region because future generations will be better able to deal with these problems than we are.
33. Laying bitumen on the Bloomfield Track would be beneficial for the environment
34. The Bloomfield Track is important because it allows quick access to remote areas of the North.
35. The more that it is possible for the average North Queensland resident can access the Bloomfield Track the better
36. I think that both short and long term perspectives are needed in deciding what should be done with the Bloomfield Track, but I don't know which one is more important.
37. Erosion from the Bloomfield Track does not cause siltation or damage to the fringing inshore reefs between Cape Tribulation and Cooktown
38. Native animals in the Daintree need protection because they have a right to life which cannot be traded against economic considerations.
39. There is no reason to believe that the Daintree Rainforest is under threat.
40. Economic development associated with the Bloomfield Track will provide more opportunities for future generations in North Queensland.
41. I'm concerned that I will be made worse off by any decision about the Bloomfield Track.
42. The most important use of the Bloomfield Track is for tourism.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 5 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 5, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 5 the option you support the least.

3. Upgrade the track to a bitumen road.
4. Close the road and rehabilitate it.
5. Upgrade the road, to a dirt road suitable for conventional vehicles.

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Prioritized maintaining the road as a 4WD track to balance environmental concerns with community access and tourism needs.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 48 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 48 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 48 lines in total.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. It would be a great thing if voters could vote on specific issues, not only on a whole party program at election time.
2. Democracy means that all policy is exposed to open discussion and debate in a public political space of all citizens before being put to a transparent, accountable vote.
3. The only time we are all equal is when we vote in the ballot box.
4. I don't know too much about democracy. I feel ridiculous voting.
5. Republicanism is a smokescreen for democratic treachery, incompetence and lunacy.
6. People are quite capable of processing and thinking about the vast majority of issues facing our society but as long as we are subjected to 'news lite' the level of political debate will remain facile. 
7. We should strengthen protections of the free press in order to facilitate a more open and publicly accountable government. 
8. Concluding that some races/cultures are better than others must be avoided.
9. If you want your vote to count for anything, then you need to not vote in ignorance, you need to know something about what you're being offered.
10. Sometimes I get a bit worried that there's a lot of small minority groups that tend to get a lot of the say
11. People get the government they deserve
12. The true function of government is to maintain peace and justice. This does not include interfering in private transactions of its electors.
13. We as individuals have a right, that's what democracy means to me
14. Governments can talk a great game about 'democracy'. They fall down, in practice, because they cannot accept any sharing of the power to influence decisions with those who might have different motives and ideas.
15. Our government is attempting to mould our society to the needs of a profit-oriented market
16. Democracy is a term which has lost much of its original meaning.
17. In the Senate there should be elected representatives who are not from the major parties but from smaller interest groups.
18. In Australia the rich have virtually unlimited access to the legal system and the capacity to use it to achieve their own ends.
19. I'm always cynical about government processes.
20. I don't want to be in a place where only a minority's viewpoint gets the right to say what's going to happen.
21. Our political system's strength is that it can change to meet changing circumstances.
22. If Australia is to recover from the horrible mess we are in at present, we will need leaders of high principles, who will govern with honesty, justice, and righteousness, fearlessly putting into practice the principles of the Bible.
23. Proportional Representation also forces parties to coalesce and moderates out the extreme political views. 
24. Until women are equally represented in Australian parliaments, we will not have a genuine representative democracy.
25. Democracy means we, the people, are responsible for what government does, or fails to do.
26. Low female participation rates compound the domination of the public realm by males.
27. The party system is the main obstruction to accountable politics.
28. The last thing we need is a Canberra 'Big Brother' telling us what we should read and hear.
29. We live in a great democracy.
30. Not voting is a form of expression. It's a way of telling parties that no one is offering policies that appeal to you.
31. Our community and nation should invoke a spirit that you are important, that you do have a way of influencing things.
32. The fundamental dynamic of Australian society is that it is one of evolution, not revolution.
33. We should not be afraid of disagreement. Indeed, an important feature of a liberal democracy is respect for conflicting ideas; difference is part of the human condition. 
34. I don't think there's anything wrong with people voting for their self-interest.
35. I suppose we do have an upper class and a lower class.
36. There's a dollar democracy that runs through our supposed democracy.
37. We suffer a Parliamentary Democracy and an archaic and conflict oriented, "two party system" where one of two main parties will manipulate us for the next few years. 
38. The people we elect are loyal not to we dumb bunnies who elected them, but the agenda and dogma of their party. 
39. There is a lot of consultation by govt – but who is listening?  And what power do they have to make changes?
40. Too few people have a lot of sway in the system.  Corporate lobbyists, vested interests, pork barrelling and contributions to political parties are all problematic.
41. The true believers are about decency in life, about a capacity to debate the issues and to receive different views.
42. The political system is remote and closed and the connection with elected representatives is difficult, they are often faceless.
43. A lot of people may be politically ignorant, but they believe what they see and hear on television, and that makes them vote the way they do. They have been brainwashed by the clever advertising people.
44. There is no real difference in ideological terms between the major parties and preference distributions are problematic.
45. Free markets work because individual people, cooperating peacefully and voluntarily through markets, can achieve much that politicians and bureaucrats cannot achieve using compulsion and direction.
46. I don't think we have a lot of input into legislation and a lot of things that are important.
47. We are a democratic country.
48. You don't have to wait three years to say 'I'm not happy with the job you did.' You can apply pressure, and enough people writing to the local member can turn the situation around.

1. A government with constitutional rules specifying its main task is to ensure that economic markets work well, and that government intervenes as little in society beyond that
2. Government with strong leaders and legislation that ensures that proper moral principles are observed in society.
3. Government that abolishes all policies that give special benefits to minority groups, and instead ensures equal influence for all Australians

27. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.

29. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.
30. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
31. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
32. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
33. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
34. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
35. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
36. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
37. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
38. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.

42. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.

## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 45 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 45 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 45 lines in total.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
2. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
3. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
4. Coal gasification is needed to produce hydrogen on the scale required for a possible transition to a hydrogen-based economy.
5. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts. 
6. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
7. The urgency of addressing greenhouse emissions cannot stay on back burner for too much longer. So we need to find a solution quickly, such as CO2 capture and storage.
8.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
9. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
10. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
11. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
12. If the cost of greenhouse gas emissions is factored in, the cost of renewables compared to coal isn't so big.
13. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
14. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
15. Governments must fund new infrastructure investment in the face of uncertainty in the economics of energy technologies.
16. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
17. Australia doesn't support alternative energy opportunities. Industry comes along and says, 'Have I got something for you' (such as carbon sequestration, or a new power station) and they get government subsidies to do it.
18. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
19. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
20. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
21. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
22. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
23. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
24. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
25. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
26. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
27. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
28. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
29. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
30. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
31. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
32. Apart from coal, natural gas is the only other potentially reliable source of power for the state.
33. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
34. Energy technologies such as nuclear power and geosequestration are too risky. It's better to improve the technologies that we already have.
35. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
36. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
37. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
38. Environmental, reliability and cost issues will limit the adoption of large-scale  of certain renewable technologies. 
39. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
40. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
41. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
42. Australia spends too much on research and development in energy technologies.
43. Reducing greenhouse gases should not mean prices have to go up.
44. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
45. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.

15. If human genome editing is available then it should be available to everyone who needs it, not just those who can afford it.
16. Parents and guardians have a right to edit the genes of their children before they are born.
17. It is better to accept our genes the way they are than to tamper with things we don't understand.
18. I think we should keep an open mind about new discoveries.
19. If we open the box of genome editing we will not know where to draw the line.

22. Anything that's been artificially created in a lab gives me Frankenstein vibes.
23. Genome editing is really cool science.
24. Beacause of our changing environments, I believe that future humans will need genome editing to survive.
25. Genome editing technologies gives us power over human life itself.
26. As a society, we have an obligation to help strengthen coming generations by eradicating diseases.

30. We find strength when we face illness and adversity. It makes us who we are. 
31. Suggesting genome editing will 'cure' disability diminishes those living with genetic conditions who need support.
32. I am concerned that the use of human genome editing will advantage one group over another.
33. If human genome editing can be used to make changes to humans on demand for any reason, the future will be like a dystopian movie.
34. I'm worried that human genome editing will widen the gap between those who can afford it and those who can't.
35. I think it's okay to use genome editing to change someone's appearance.
36. If genome editing is proven to be safe, then I see no reason to oppose it.
37. Parents want 'designer babies' with certain traits out of vanity.
38. I'm concerned that genome editing will be used as a quick techno-fix without actually dealing with real problems.
39. I don't think we know enough about genetic diseases or the long term consequences of genome editing
40. Science and technology have too much control over our lives.
41. The idea of editing the human genome is scary.
42. Decisions about the use of genome editing are best left to the experts.
43. Editing genes that will be inherited is problematic because it means making decisions for future people who don't exist yet. 
44. It's better to use genome editing to prevent a serious disease from happening rather than having to treat it with conventional medicine after it has occurred.
45. I would consider using genome editing for my children to give them an advantage in life, so long as it's safe.

## [Considerations]:
1. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
2. We have to move forward with large-scale restoration-based fuel reduction and learn as we go.
3. If an action is determined to be necessary to control a wildfire, save lives and/or property, and ensure that fire crews can do their jobs safely and efficiently, then it is appropriate to act even if it results in the take of an endangered species.
4. Forests must contribute to the economic stability of forest-dependent communities.  There are many job opportunities and value-added products that come out of the forest such as wood for art, vigas for building homes, wildlife for food, herbs for medicine, and grass for livestock.
5. Land managers should return public forest land to natural conditions and fire cycles that are specific to each forest-type.
6. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
7. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.
8. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
9. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.
10. Old Growth protection is necessary in order to preserve and protect the viability of species dependent upon Old Growth ecosystems.
11. Without public participation there will be conflict, whereas participation leads to cooperation.
12. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
13. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
14. Large trees must be removed in order to create openings for wildlife habitat. 
15. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
16. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
17. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science. 
18. Forest health means jobs.
19. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
20. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
21. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
22. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
23. Returning forests to presettlement conditions ignores the need for wildlife that are adapted to current forest conditions by mandating drastic thinning virtually overnight. 
24. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
25. Federal land management procedures are so complex that they prevent timely action to address ecological crises on public lands.
26. Forest health needs restoring after decades of government mismanagement.
27. We need to be cautious: the solution is there, but we still have a lot to learn. If we just jump in, we're going to make mistakes.
28. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.
29. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.
30. Demonizing fire is a mistake: we must accept risks of fire damage to property and implement controlled burning.
31. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
32. Federal agencies need to restore public trust through transparency in project intent, development and implementation.
33. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
34. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
35. Prescribed burns are a flawed idea, especially when there are other practices available for restoration.
36. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
37. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.
38. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
39. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.
40. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
41. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
42. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.

## [Considerations]:
1. Can we be confident, that if we store CO2 the storage facility is going to hold it forever? That's really the issue. And I don't think anybody can answer that question.
2. The limited strategic and technical insight that is so entrenched in Australia is limiting the development of innovative energy technologies.
3. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.
4. Combining technologies in the energy sector is a much more promising and more productive approach than relying on a single approach. 
5. I'm not pro-nuclear, I'm not pro-coal, I'm not pro-wind, I'm not pro any kind of generation. I'm pro-energy conservation through changes to our behavioural and design practices.
6. I don't want the implementation of new energy technologies to disrupt my way of life.
7. Natural gas is the bridging fuel between the oil economy and the hydrogen economy.
8. Any return on geosequestration is 15 to 20 years off, whereas the proven technology of renewable energy offers immediate gains.
9. Australia should  turn more attention to biomass energy sources because it is CO2 neutral (the carbon dioxide used by the growing plants is released when they are burned).
10. Solar power is pointless because it can't guarantee constant supply, for obvious reasons: the sun doesn't always shine.
11. The petroleum age is far from over, we will still be able to keep finding more oil.
12. Energy is going to get costly so we had better start investing in alternatives.
13. Nuclear has a few dangers, but they're trivial compared with the dangers of emitting greenhouse gases and letting global warming happen.
14. Wind power has its downsides — it is highly visible and can kill birds. The fact is though, that any man-made structure can kill birds.	
15. Nuclear is the inevitable replacement for old hydrocarbon technology. It is cost-competitive with coal and will cogenerate potable water and hydrogen also at societally acceptable costs.
16. Local energy solutions such as windfarms are good for jobs, local economies and tourism.
17. It is very hard to trust all these so-called experts arguing for one energy technology or another, especially when they, or their bosses, are just in it to make money.
18. Coal-powered energy needs to be minimised because of its high greenhouse gas emissions.
19. We need coal because it is a cheap and reliable energy source.
20. Reducing our reliance on oil would be good for the economy and the environment.
21. Renewables are part of the long-term solution, but for the foreseeable future, they just can't do the job.
22. Our present energy system is so cheap precisely because it is unsustainable.
23. There is no need make expensive investments in technological changes within the energy sector.
24. You could have a wind farm across all of the outback that would kill every kookaburra, but it wouldn't provide the baseload power we need.
25. Geothermal or hot rock technology will provide a reliable and unlimited and cheap energy source.
26. Any tax to reduce greenhouse gas emissions will have a detrimental economic effect on the nation.
27. Rather than look at costly renewable energy a more fair-dinkum strategy would be to encourage technology that captures greenhouse emissions like carbon dioxide.
28. Fuzzy-headed thinking about alternative energy sources seems not to appreciate the need for certainty of supply and excess capacity to keep economies growing.
29. Nuclear power is a more proven technology than it was 30 years ago. In reality atomic power generation can be a very safe system if designed and operated correctly.
30. Prices of alternative energy will fall as technology improves.
31. Many big ticket solutions to energy problems that we don't understand are just too risky.
32.  If Australia mines uranium, the country should be able to generate power from it.
33. Using biomass from crops has significant expansion potential and would be good for the rural industry.
34. Renewable sources do not have the potential to meet our future energy needs as they stand.
35. Energy technologies are pretty complex, so I leave it to the experts.

## [Considerations]:
1. Genetic research will improve our lives.
2. Permission from the indigenous community must be sought if samples are collected from indigenous peoples.
3. I trust researchers to make sure only approved people get access to my samples
4. Commercial companies should keep all the profits they make from biobanking because they take the financial risks and put up the money to develop new drugs and treatments.
5. Religious groups need to be asked for their views about biobanks and genetic research.
6. There must be special consideration of the views of Aboriginal people towards healthcare and genetic research.
7. There is no risk to the people who provide samples and information to biobanks.
8. The public will be more protected if biobanks are government-funded not privately funded.
9. People who provide samples for research should get special access to the treatments that result from this research.
10. I don't mind if my samples are connected to my medical records without my prior permission, so long as researchers don't get access to any data that identifies me.
11. The biobank owner should be able to sell any information they have about my genes, if they want to.
12. High-priced genetic research is diverting funds that could be used to promote public health in other ways.
13. People should always be able to withdraw their sample from research at any time.
14. It is always acceptable to do research on samples that identify me, without my prior permission.
15. Profits from biobanking should be shared in some way with the community who provided the samples.
16. Collecting samples from people in an ethnic or cultural group is acceptable only if the whole group has agreed to participate.
17. The confidentiality of personal medical information is critical in any circumstance where research is being conducted.
18. I do not mind if my sample is connected to my name and medical information.
19. I should be asked for my permission every time researchers want to use my samples for research
20. Biobanks are valuable because they promise huge benefits for our economy.
21. People should be paid for providing their samples to a biobank.
22. I trust biobanks with managers who are independent of researchers to make sure only approved people get access to my samples
23. My sample should never be permanently anonymized since I should be contacted about important research results
24. I do not mind if researchers have access to my samples, when there is no way I can be identified.
25. It is acceptable for samples and information that doesn't identify me to be sent to researchers overseas.
26. Race is a useful topic for genetic studies
27. Public funds should pay for biobanks, instead of private companies.
28. It's OK if data that identifies me is stored in a separate database and replaced in the biobank by a unique non-identifying code.
29. Researchers and institutions (e.g. hospitals and universities) should be allowed to use samples for research but they should not own them.
30. Policy makers need to consider whether WA should not have biobanks.
31. Improved health is more likely to come from educating people about their diet and lifestyle than from biobanks.
32. Biobanks need to be monitored and reviewed by external, independent people to prevent the misuse of data and samples.
33. I should have property rights to my tissues before and after they leave my body
34. Genetic studies of race on ethnic or cultural groups will lead to the discrimination of those groups.
35. People should be told if commercial companies could get access to their samples and information.
36. I trust independent research ethics committees, which are not connected to the biobank in anyway, to decide whether research is ethical and approve who gets access to my samples.
37. There is no point asking the public for their views on the ethical issues in science and technology.
38. The priorities for health should be to reduce inequalities and the burden of disease.
39. People who provide samples should be active in the set up and ongoing management of biobanks.
40. We should all provide samples to biobanks because it will benefit everyone.
41. Commercial companies should get access to biobanks, otherwise new drugs and treatments will not be developed.
42. Biobanks are valuable even if they only advance science (e.g. provide new information about diseases) and do not lead to treatments or cures.
43. Biobanks will only lead to high profits and expensive treatments that most people can't afford.
44. Genetic studies will lead to the discrimination of people living with genetic conditions or disabilities.
45. People with a [chronic disease or] genetic condition in their family have a responsibility to be involved in genetic research.
46. The community that provides samples for research should receive improved medical services in return.
47. Information about people's genes and the traits they inherit from their parents is more private than their medical records.
48. The fact that we cannot predict what biobanks will be used for in the future bothers me.
49. Deciding how to regulate biobanks should be left to the government.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.

- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.

1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Publicly Funded with strong regulation: A biobanking system owned and run by the government, who is also responsible for oversight and privacy provisions, as well as controlling access.
2. Privately Funded with minimal regulation: Minimal regulation of privately run biobanking system with maximum participation of the public. Low privacy provisions.
3. High Privacy: Implementation of a (publicy or privately owned) biobanking system where privacy of individuals is paramount. Stored data and biological samples for research requires the authorization of individual donors.
4. Privately Funded with strong regulation: A BB system where funding is provided mostly by private companies, withstrong government oversight and privacy provisions.
5. Cautious Implementation: Minimal input of public resources to development biobanking Use resources  — use instead for other approaches to improving health. Very strict oversight of use of biobanks and strong privacy provisions.
6. Publicly Funded with minimal regulation: A biobanking system owned and run by the government, who is also responsible for oversight and privacy provisions, as well as controlling access.
7. Minimal Government Input: Minimal input of public resources to development biobanking Use resources  — use instead for other approaches to improving health. Fairly relaxed oversight of use of biobanks and  privacy provisions (low level of regulation).

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Strongly favor public funding with regulation and privacy focus over private minimal regulation systems due to trust and ethical concerns.

- Rate each of the 48 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 48 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 48 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Democracy means we, the people, are responsible for what government does, or fails to do.
2. I'm always cynical about government processes.
3. The only time we are all equal is when we vote in the ballot box.
4. Proportional Representation also forces parties to coalesce and moderates out the extreme political views. 
5. Too few people have a lot of sway in the system.  Corporate lobbyists, vested interests, pork barrelling and contributions to political parties are all problematic.
6. The people we elect are loyal not to we dumb bunnies who elected them, but the agenda and dogma of their party. 
7. In the Senate there should be elected representatives who are not from the major parties but from smaller interest groups.
8. The true function of government is to maintain peace and justice. This does not include interfering in private transactions of its electors.
9. Low female participation rates compound the domination of the public realm by males.
10. The fundamental dynamic of Australian society is that it is one of evolution, not revolution.
11. Democracy is a term which has lost much of its original meaning.
12. We should not be afraid of disagreement. Indeed, an important feature of a liberal democracy is respect for conflicting ideas; difference is part of the human condition. 
13. Republicanism is a smokescreen for democratic treachery, incompetence and lunacy.
14. Until women are equally represented in Australian parliaments, we will not have a genuine representative democracy.
15. The political system is remote and closed and the connection with elected representatives is difficult, they are often faceless.
16. We suffer a Parliamentary Democracy and an archaic and conflict oriented, "two party system" where one of two main parties will manipulate us for the next few years. 
17. I don't think we have a lot of input into legislation and a lot of things that are important.
18. I don't think there's anything wrong with people voting for their self-interest.
19. The party system is the main obstruction to accountable politics.
20. Our community and nation should invoke a spirit that you are important, that you do have a way of influencing things.
21. The last thing we need is a Canberra 'Big Brother' telling us what we should read and hear.
22. If you want your vote to count for anything, then you need to not vote in ignorance, you need to know something about what you're being offered.
23. Governments can talk a great game about 'democracy'. They fall down, in practice, because they cannot accept any sharing of the power to influence decisions with those who might have different motives and ideas.
24. We are a democratic country.
25. Not voting is a form of expression. It's a way of telling parties that no one is offering policies that appeal to you.
26. I suppose we do have an upper class and a lower class.
27. People get the government they deserve
28. There is a lot of consultation by govt – but who is listening?  And what power do they have to make changes?
29. We should strengthen protections of the free press in order to facilitate a more open and publicly accountable government. 
30. We as individuals have a right, that's what democracy means to me
31. Our political system's strength is that it can change to meet changing circumstances.
32. There's a dollar democracy that runs through our supposed democracy.
33. People are quite capable of processing and thinking about the vast majority of issues facing our society but as long as we are subjected to 'news lite' the level of political debate will remain facile. 
34. In Australia the rich have virtually unlimited access to the legal system and the capacity to use it to achieve their own ends.
35. You don't have to wait three years to say 'I'm not happy with the job you did.' You can apply pressure, and enough people writing to the local member can turn the situation around.
36. The true believers are about decency in life, about a capacity to debate the issues and to receive different views.
37. I don't want to be in a place where only a minority's viewpoint gets the right to say what's going to happen.
38. Our government is attempting to mould our society to the needs of a profit-oriented market
39. We live in a great democracy.
40. A lot of people may be politically ignorant, but they believe what they see and hear on television, and that makes them vote the way they do. They have been brainwashed by the clever advertising people.
41. I don't know too much about democracy. I feel ridiculous voting.
42. If Australia is to recover from the horrible mess we are in at present, we will need leaders of high principles, who will govern with honesty, justice, and righteousness, fearlessly putting into practice the principles of the Bible.
43. Democracy means that all policy is exposed to open discussion and debate in a public political space of all citizens before being put to a transparent, accountable vote.
44. Sometimes I get a bit worried that there's a lot of small minority groups that tend to get a lot of the say
45. Concluding that some races/cultures are better than others must be avoided.
46. There is no real difference in ideological terms between the major parties and preference distributions are problematic.
47. It would be a great thing if voters could vote on specific issues, not only on a whole party program at election time.
48. Free markets work because individual people, cooperating peacefully and voluntarily through markets, can achieve much that politicians and bureaucrats cannot achieve using compulsion and direction.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 5 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 5, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 5 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 5 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 5 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Government that abolishes all policies that give special benefits to minority groups, and instead ensures equal influence for all Australians
2. Government with guaranteed involvement by all social groups, especially those representing disadvantaged minorities, in policy making
3. Government with strong leaders and legislation that ensures that proper moral principles are observed in society.
4. A government with constitutional rules specifying its main task is to ensure that economic markets work well, and that government intervenes as little in society beyond that
5. The kind of government that we have, with no major changes

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Prioritized inclusive governance valuing diverse input while ensuring moral principles and market efficiency.

8. Natural resources must be developed for the benefit of the plain American citizen.

10. Stakeholders in forest management should work together to define management objectives more by experiments and adaptive management. 
11. All fuels treatment projects on public lands should comply with existing environmental laws even if compliance slows implementation.
12. Prescribed burning is needed to restore fire-adapted ecosystems.

14. We need active forest management on our public lands, through thinning and prescribed burns to reduce the unnatural buildup of fuels.

17. We need to clean up the bureaucratic maze that stops our professional foresters from being able to do the work that they are trained to do.

19. People should take what is needed from forests, but in a context of stewardship and sustainable use and interaction with nature. 
20. Using citizen participation in forest management is very important for basing decisions on different ideas and cultural values along with science.

24. Environmental organizations have moved the management of our forests to where it is being done by emotion and not by science.
25. Forest lands should be brought back to their state before human intervention began.
26. Thinning efforts should focus entirely on the small trees that make up the vast majority of the fire risk in the forest. 
27. Needless red tape and lawsuits delay effective implementation of forest health projects on public lands.
28. The government is advancing timber sales in the name of ecological restoration.
29. We need to experiment with a range of treatments that could meet restoration goals. 
30. Forest restoration projects should be done in all areas of the forest including roadless and wilderness areas.
31. The increased density of forests in the West has not damaged ecosystems.
32. We should not manipulate nature by restoring forest conditions.
33. A diameter cap should be placed on all thinning projects to ensure large trees are not cut.
34. Aggressive fire suppression has caused the majority of the problems regarding  fires. 
35. To make thinning projects cost effective, private logging companies must be able to log larger trees.
36. Fire risk reduction projects should clearly focus on the wildland-urban interface, avoiding treatments in roadless areas.
37. The main issue in forest management is to protect loss of life and property due to catastrophic wildfire. 
38. Forest management involves restoring ecosystem function and processes that maintain ecosystems over the long run. 
39. Traditional, sustainable forestry that benefits local economies and maintains rural livelihoods is much better than large scale corporate forestry.
40. We need to allow forest managers to determine how to improve forest health to minimize fire damage and loss.
41. Federal forest management policy should make it easier for loggers to thin out backcountry forests by easing regulatory restrictions and making it harder for interest groups to stop or delay that work.
42. Science is the most important component informing all management decisions — more so than social, cultural and economic considerations.
43. Small scale thinning projects should give the communities involved pride in taking part in a sustainable forest management plan, and it also allows the traditional communities to realize a boost to their fragile economies.
44. Humans are a part of the environment. We need to learn how to live sustainably with that environment as much as possible. 
45. Fire is a natural and vital component of most western forest ecosystems.

- Rate each of the 38 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 38 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 38 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Biobanks are useful even if they only produce more scientific knowledge and not medical advancements.
2. I do not care if my donated sample is connected to my name and medical information.
3. Genetic research will improve our lives.
4. Everyone should donate samples to a biobank for the benefit of everyone. 
5. High-priced genetic research is diverting funds that could be used to promote public health.
6. The community that donates samples for research should receive improved medical services.  
7. Biobanks need independent review boards to determine who should have access to samples. 
8. Researchers should be allowed to use samples for research but they should not own them.  
9. Public funds should pay for biobanks, instead of private companies.  
10. Race is a useful topic for genetic studies.
11. Participants should always be able to withdraw their sample from research at anytime. 
12. The priority for healthcare should be to reduce inequalities and the burden of disease.
13. The confidentiality of personal medical information is critical in any circumstance where research is being conducted.
14. Educating people about health issues (e.g. diet and lifestyle changes) promises greater health effects than investing in biobanks.
15. Scientists should have access to all unidentified, personal samples for research.
16. Policy makers should consider the possibility that Canada should not pursue biobanking.
17. If someone is a carrier of a genetic disease, they have a responsibility to participate in genetic research.
18. My personal sample should never be anonymized since I should be informed of important research results.  
19. Sampling some people in an ethnocultural community is acceptable only if the whole ethnocultural community has agreed to participate.
20. Deciding how to regulate biobanks should be left to the government. 
21. I trust researchers to control access to my personal samples.
22. Aboriginal communities require special consideration concerning healthcare and research.
23. Participants should be contacted every time researchers want to use their samples for research.
24. Permission from the indigenous community must be sought if samples are collected from indigenous peoples.
25. Genetic studies of race on enthocultural communities will lead to the discrimination of those same enthocultural communities. 
26. Genetic information is different from health information. 
27. All participants should be paid for donating their samples to a biobank. 
28. There is no point in consulting the public about ethical issues in science and technology.
29. Participants who donate their samples for research should be given special access to the treatments and therapies that result from that research. 
30. To me, religious communities need to be consulted about genetic and biobank research. 
31. Genetic studies of disability will lead to the discrimination of people living with the same conditions.
32. I should have property rights to my tissues before or after they leave my body.
33. The fact that we cannot predict what biobanks will be used for bothers me. 
34. Biobanks will only lead to expensive treatments and high profits. 
35. Participants should be active in the set up and oversight of  biobanks. 
36. Profits from biobanking should be returned to the donating community. 
37. There is no risk to the participants who donate to biobanks.
38. It is always permissible to do research on my personally identifiable sample without my prior permission.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g., research ethics board), regardless of whether the individual is identifiable.
2. Every use of stored data and biological samples for research requires the authorization of individuals, even if the use does not identify the individual.
3. Regardless of privacy and oversight, it is most important to prevent discrimination (e.g., through insurance, social attitudes) that might result from research on collections of data and biological samples.
4. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g., research ethics board), ONLY when the individual is identifiable.
5. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires authorization from individuals ONLY when the individual is identifiable.
6. Regardless of privacy and oversight, it is most important to ensure benefits to society or the community (e.g., geographical, ethno-cultural) participating in a collection of data and biological samples.
7. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires authorization from individuals only when they are identifiable AND approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g. research ethics board) when they are not identifiable.

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Prioritize governing body approval and societal benefits while limiting individual authorization demands.

- Rate each of the 38 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 38 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 38 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Participants should always be able to withdraw their sample from research at anytime. 
2. Genetic information is different from health information. 
3. There is no risk to the participants who donate to biobanks.
4. I do not care if my donated sample is connected to my name and medical information.
5. To me, religious communities need to be consulted about genetic and biobank research. 
6. Researchers should be allowed to use samples for research but they should not own them.  
7. Genetic research will improve our lives.
8. The fact that we cannot predict what biobanks will be used for bothers me. 
9. Educating people about health issues (e.g. diet and lifestyle changes) promises greater health effects than investing in biobanks.
10. Genetic studies of race on enthocultural communities will lead to the discrimination of those same enthocultural communities. 
11. I should have property rights to my tissues before or after they leave my body.
12. Genetic studies of disability will lead to the discrimination of people living with the same conditions.
13. Biobanks are useful even if they only produce more scientific knowledge and not medical advancements.
14. The priority for healthcare should be to reduce inequalities and the burden of disease.
15. Policy makers should consider the possibility that Canada should not pursue biobanking.
16. Biobanks will only lead to expensive treatments and high profits. 
17. Deciding how to regulate biobanks should be left to the government. 
18. There is no point in consulting the public about ethical issues in science and technology.
19. High-priced genetic research is diverting funds that could be used to promote public health.
20. All participants should be paid for donating their samples to a biobank. 
21. Participants should be active in the set up and oversight of  biobanks. 
22. Scientists should have access to all unidentified, personal samples for research.
23. Profits from biobanking should be returned to the donating community. 
24. My personal sample should never be anonymized since I should be informed of important research results.  
25. If someone is a carrier of a genetic disease, they have a responsibility to participate in genetic research.
26. It is always permissible to do research on my personally identifiable sample without my prior permission.  
27. The confidentiality of personal medical information is critical in any circumstance where research is being conducted.
28. The community that donates samples for research should receive improved medical services.  
29. I trust researchers to control access to my personal samples.
30. Everyone should donate samples to a biobank for the benefit of everyone. 
31. Public funds should pay for biobanks, instead of private companies.  
32. Race is a useful topic for genetic studies.
33. Biobanks need independent review boards to determine who should have access to samples. 
34. Participants should be contacted every time researchers want to use their samples for research.
35. Permission from the indigenous community must be sought if samples are collected from indigenous peoples.
36. Participants who donate their samples for research should be given special access to the treatments and therapies that result from that research. 
37. Sampling some people in an ethnocultural community is acceptable only if the whole ethnocultural community has agreed to participate.
38. Aboriginal communities require special consideration concerning healthcare and research.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Every use of stored data and biological samples for research requires the authorization of individuals, even if the use does not identify the individual.
2. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g., research ethics board), regardless of whether the individual is identifiable.
3. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires authorization from individuals only when they are identifiable AND approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g. research ethics board) when they are not identifiable.
4. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires authorization from individuals ONLY when the individual is identifiable.
5. Regardless of privacy and oversight, it is most important to prevent discrimination (e.g., through insurance, social attitudes) that might result from research on collections of data and biological samples.
6. Use of stored data and biological samples for research requires approval by an appropriate governing body (e.g., research ethics board), ONLY when the individual is identifiable.
7. Regardless of privacy and oversight, it is most important to ensure benefits to society or the community (e.g., geographical, ethno-cultural) participating in a collection of data and biological samples.

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Balanced approach prioritizing oversight and individual rights while valuing societal benefits and preventing harm.

- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.

response: Prioritized significant emissions cuts and adaptation focusing on resilience community involvement and local action over inaction or growth-centric policies.

42. Climate change considerations have no role in the development of national and global energy policies.

## [Considerations]:
1. the fusion is a leap in the unknown
2. the fusion is a samll step to complete a path of amalgamation that started 20 years ago. The amalgamated municipality it is a realty in facts. How much do we have to wait still?
3. the shift from the union to the fusion is a step to big which brings too many uncertainties. If things are done more gradually the change will be hurtless because people will be already used to it.
4. the fusion will bring the resources to make the intervention that our territory needs, like the bycicle paths or the public transport between the municipalities or the high school.
5. the fusion is necessary to lower the taxes
6. the amalgsmation will offer the possibility of save money by cutting the political costs and the burocracy costs and making the administration more efficient.
7. the fusion is too risky because is a oneway process
8. it is not possible to say yes or not to the amalgamation without knowing how it will be, how much will it cost and how it will be done.
9. it is not necessary to be big to be good. The small municipalities can be better managed of the bigger and do more things. It is a matter of good administration.
10. the union is a failure and a cost, because it absorbed just a very small part of the services and the money
11. the needs of the citizens are too different acros the municipalities. It will be too difficult for The amalgameted municipality to answer to everybody.
12. I would not like that the money of my taxes would be used in the municiplities next to mine
13. there are not enoughf elements do decide in favor or against the fusion
14. the fusion is a decision that has already been taken and they are trying to imposing it top down. They are trying to sell the product "amalgamated municipality"
15. the choice of the fusion is due to the wish of certain political parties to maintain the political dominance
16. the fusion is not the only solution to the issues of our territory but it is the more concrete
17. the fusion benefits the bigger mnicipalities at the detriment of the smalles also with respect to the external fundings.
18. if the fusion will not be done, the single municipalities will not be capable of maintaining the current quality of the services.
19. in this fusion there is no project, no vision and nos trategy. Things should be done in a very different way.
20. with or without the amalgamation, the important thing that is at the practical level, nothing will change. For example the offices should stay where they are.
21. through the fusion we will be able to exploit the potentials of the territory to improve the building-, commercial- handcraft- and agricoltural development.
22. the amalgamation will benefit the emplyees and the citizens. The emplyees will increase their competences through more trainings. Therefore the citizens will benefit of more specialized professionals.
23. it is not yet clear how are they are going to amalgamate the contracts of the municipal clerks across the territory. things like these should be decided before the amalgamtion.
24. the fusion is an innovative process that will make as an example to follow for italy and the rest of europe.
25. in this days of crisis and changes at the european level, the amalgamation is necessary and opportune.
26. with the amalgamation there will be a deficit of democracy because the municipalities will be only consultive. The citizens will have no power
27. through the fusion we will be able to derogare il patto di stabilita' and therefore unblock some founds. The latter can be invested in the municipalities that are more in need 
28. the consequence of the fusion is that either we will pay more than before or they will cut the services
29. the fusion will change our relationship with the administration. The fusionwill move away the administration and the power from the local territory and centralizing it somwhere else
30. if the administration chose for the fusion it means that it is the right choice. This choice should be taken by the experts not the citizens
31. it is not worth to make the amalgamation in this time of reorganization with the metropolitan bologna
32. we are misusing the fusion. The needs of the territory are not being respected and the valsmaoggia is being used as a labrat
33. the fusion is the right answer to the limit of the union
34. the new municipality will be politically more powerful in front of other municipalities like Bologna metropolitan. In this way our interests will be protected outside our municiplity.
35. the fusion seem to me another way to change everything to change nothing
36. the amalgamation will erease the local diversities
